# Try and Catch üõ°Ô∏è

The `try` statement lets you test a block of code for errors.
The `catch` statement lets you handle the error.

```javascript
try {
  alert("Working...");
  alert(undefinedVariable); // Error occurs here!
} catch (err) {
  console.log("An error occurred: " + err.message);
}
```
With this, your script **continues** running!

# Finally üèÅ

The `finally` statement lets you execute code, after try and catch, regardless of the result.

```javascript
try {
  // Code to run
} catch (err) {
  // Handle errors
} finally {
  // Always runs (clean up)
  console.log("Done trying.");
}
```

# The Error Object üìú

JavaScript has a built-in error object that provides error information.

Properties:
- `name`: Sets or returns an error name.
- `message`: Sets or returns an error message.

```javascript
try {
  decodeURI("%%%");
} catch (err) {
  console.log(err.name);    // "URIError"
  console.log(err.message); // "URI malformed"
}
```
